---
import CaseStudy from '../../layouts/CaseStudy.astro';
import SpendChart from '../../components/charts/SpendChart.jsx';
---

<CaseStudy
  title="Credit-card spend tracker"
  category="Data engineering · Analysis · Visualisation"
  status="Anonymised"
  summary="An end-to-end pipeline that turns raw multi-bank card statements into an interactive spending dashboard — sourcing, SQL modelling, analysis and visualisation."
  role="Sole builder"
  year="2026"
  stack={['Python', 'SQLite', 'SQL', 'Chart.js', 'Gmail API']}
>
  <p class="note">Built originally on my own family's finances; every figure here is <strong>synthetic</strong>. No real account numbers, balances, merchants or personal data appear — this shows the method and the dashboard, never the statements.</p>

  <section class="stage" id="source">
    <h2>1 · Source</h2>
    <p>Statements arrive by email from several banks. A small Python ingester (Gmail API) pulls the monthly attachments automatically into a raw store — no manual downloading, and a repeatable, auditable intake.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="stage" id="engineer">
    <h2>2 · Engineer (SQL)</h2>
    <p>Transactions are parsed and normalised into a SQLite <strong>single source of truth</strong> — a typed schema for cards, statements and transactions (date, merchant, category, direction, local + foreign amount and currency). An idempotent sync step rebuilds the dashboard data from the database, so a re-run with no changes is a no-op.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="stage" id="analyse">
    <h2>3 · Analyse</h2>
    <p>With clean data, the questions are easy: where the money goes by category and month, how spend compares to repayments, and which months break trend. Roughly 750 transactions across two cards, multi-currency, were categorised and rolled up.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="stage" id="visualise">
    <h2>4 · Visualise</h2>
    <figure class="viz">
      <SpendChart client:visible />
      <figcaption>Monthly spend by category — synthetic sample. Toggle a category to focus it.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>The real dashboard is a themed Chart.js front-end with a documented v1 → v2 redesign that added a unified design system, WCAG-AA contrast, tabular numerals, focus-visible states and reduced-motion support.</p>
  </section>
</CaseStudy>
